<div class="body"><p> Then there was a rather more fiddly account that seemed to involve straightforward sampling errors: too many young, apparently enthusiastic respondents who failed to turn out on the day, and too few older, more curmudgeonly ones who were absolutely determined to turn out. </p><p> <script height="302px" src="http://player.ooyala.com/iframe.js#pbid=ZTIxYmJjZDM2NWYzZDViZGRiOWJjYzc5&amp;ec=1ibjhtMDE6ArIrGztdT4yrOYLsdyI2vM" width="540px"></script><iframe frameborder="0" height="302px" src="http://player.ooyala.com/iframe.html#pbid=ZTIxYmJjZDM2NWYzZDViZGRiOWJjYzc5&amp;ec=1ibjhtMDE6ArIrGztdT4yrOYLsdyI2vM&amp;docUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.telegraph.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fnewstopics%2Feureferendum%2F12144371%2FThe-pollsters-were-wrong-about-the-election-why-believe-them-on-the-EU.html" webkitallowfullscreen="true" width="540px"></iframe></p><p> Well, maybe. But surely somebody among those highly paid estimably expert opinion analysts could have seen that happening – and made a guess, on the grounds of basic human intuition, what the consequences would be. (Hey, guys, have you noticed how many of the targets over 65 aren’t taking our calls, or available on email?) If the age thing remains a factor in the EU referendum polling, then even the latest figures, which show the Brexit camp ahead, may be wildly underestimating its lead. </p><p> But it’s that point about intuition that is the insoluble problem. What has been pretty much ruled out entirely of modern, pseudo-scientific opinion-testing is precisely the indispensable ingredient for making sense of public opinion: some sort of grasp of the human condition. If, indeed, the polling employees who were actually doing the field work – making the phone calls, sending out the emails – had noticed the difficulty in contacting (or getting the active cooperation of) older voters, what could they have done with that perception? If they had reported it, they would have been told that no free-wheeling conjecture about what this might mean could be permitted. No doubt this prohibition on personal judgment would be regarded as essential to avoid “bias”: the collation of data must be free of prejudice or the kind of educated guesswork that makes social functioning possible in most spheres of life. </p><p>
</p><div class="tg-pullquote__content tg-pullquote__global__group">
<style type="text/css">.tg-pullquote__global__group{zoom: 1;}.tg-pullquote__global__group:before, .tg-pullquote__global__group:after{content: ""; display: table;}.tg-pullquote__global__group:after{clear: both;}.tg-pullquote__inline{float:left;}.tg-pullquote__content{margin: 0 20px 10px 0px; font-size:18px; line-height:23px; font-family:georgia; width:260px; float:left;}.tg-pullquote__content--mobile{float: none; font-size: 18px; margin-left: 4.687%; margin-right: 4.687%; width: 90.626%;}.tg-pullquote__title{font-family:arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:16px; border-top:1px dotted #000000;}.tg-pullquote__quote{color:#007A8F; font-style:italic; margin-top:5px; margin-bottom:5px;}.tg-pullquote__attribution{color:#787878; margin-bottom:5px;}.tg-pullquote__source{}.tg-pullquote__source__link{color:#234B7B; outline:0; text-decoration:none;}.tg-pullquote__source__link:hover{border-bottom: 1px dotted #122842; color: #122842;}.tg-pullquote__share{float:right;}.tg-pullquote__share--icon{background-image:url("http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/pullQuotes/assets/share_sprite.png"); background-image: url("http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/pullQuotes/assets/share_sprite.svg"), none; width:26px; height:26px;}.tg-pullquote__shareLink{border-bottom:none;}.tg-pullquote__shareLink:hover{border-bottom:none !important;}.tg-pullquote__share--twitter{margin-right:5px;}.tg-pullquote__share--facebook{background-position: 26px 0;}</style>
<div class="tg-pullquote__quote">
    Before the general election, when asked which leader, David Cameron or Ed Miliband, would make the best prime minister, a majority of people consistently gave the polls a reliable prediction of how they would actually vote. 
  </div>
