 the ultimate answer: it is the ultimate folly. Just when the peddlers of simplistic mathematical certainty become convinced that they have found the key to all political understanding, the people become more evasive, more mystifying, and more self-contradictory – almost as if they were determined not to be reduced to a calculable foregone conclusion. </p><p> This may be why it is so often the secondary questions that are more accurately revealing. Before the general election, when asked which leader, David Cameron or Ed Miliband, would make the best prime minister, a majority of people consistently gave the polls a reliable prediction of how they would actually vote. If, instead of Iowans being asked which candidate they were going to support, they had been asked which one they thought would be the best national leader in a global crisis, might there have been a different outcome? I suggest that the flat-footed question, who – or what, in the case of a referendum – do you support, is becoming futile. It is an invitation to cast yourself in an apparently closed-minded, no-exit definable way that is not acceptable in our fluid, mobile society which seems to offer so many possibilities for self-determination. </p><p> If this is true, then the real lesson of these mishaps is the one that should have been essential to any method of understanding politics: People Are Really Very Complicated. They are not like the experimental dogs that were taught to salivate when they heard a bell ring because they associated the sound with being fed. Tactical electoral planning relies on the assumption that voters have motives of their own – which they may or may not admit to – but it seems less able to understand that these voter-creatures have the capacity to understand, and react to, the motives of others. </p><p>
</p><div class="tg-pullquote__content tg-pullquote__global__group">
