the party that your family and your community had always supported. In Britain, this was a question of class loyalty. In the US, it was generally a matter of ethnicity and how recently your family had arrived in the country. It used to be a truism of American politics that the first generation born to immigrants were always Democrats. Later on, their children would move away from the sense of being disadvantaged outsiders and make their own political choices. I expect a similar sort of movement away from Labour will happen here as the children of immigrants become more integrated. </p><p> But the close communities with their continuity and their sense of belonging have not just broken down: they have come to be seen as depressing limitations on personal freedom. You are now expected to define yourself as an individual on every conceivable level. Each social act is a moral choice: what you do is what you are. So the current means of evaluating voter behaviour may not be ultra-modern at all. In truth, it may be hopelessly old-fashioned. </p></div>

